{"questionId":"22154878","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">R</mi><mo mathvariant=\"bold\"> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced></math> be the matrix representing a rotation, counter-clockwise (anticlockwise) about the origin, through an angle of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><div class=\"qb-leaf-part\" data-part=\"0\"><p>Use your answers from part (a) and part (b) to</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-part\" data-part=\"1\"><p>explain why <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-part\" data-part=\"2\"><p>show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced></math>.</p></div></div>","markschemeHtml":"<div class=\"qb-ms-part\" data-part=\"0\"><p>(Because matrix multiplication represents the composition of transformations) two rotations of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math> are equivalent to a rotation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so the two matrices are equal (so each of the entries are also equal)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-ms-part\" data-part=\"1\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>replacing&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo></math>with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p></div>","meta":{"questionId":"22154878","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ1.11c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Use your answers from part (a) and part (b) to explain why sin 2α=2 sin α cos α. show that cos 2α=1-2 sin2 α.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.14—Setting up a DE, solve by separating variables","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.8—Unit circle, Pythag identity, solving trig equations graphically","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Matrix transformations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
